# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ervin-g-bailey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:ervin-g-bailey/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:ervin-g-bailey/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:ervin-g-bailey/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] Bailey was born in Damascus, Ohio as son of George W.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] Bailey and Ruthetta (Butler) Bailey He obtained his MSc in Mechanical Engineering from the Ohio State University in 1903.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] After his graduation he started his career at the Fairmont Coal Company in Fairmont, West Virginia as test engineer.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] In 1907 to 1909 he was head of the coal department of Arthur D.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] Little Inc. in Boston, and from 1909 to 1915 mechanical engineer and partner in the Fuel Testing Corporation in Boston.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] In 1916 he founded the Bailey Meter Company in Boston, which he moved to Cleveland, Ohio in 1919.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] The Bailey Meter Company grew out to a major manufacturer of industrial meters and controls.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] Bailey obtained 141 patents for his inventions.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] Among the many engineering honors he received, the Franklin Institute awarded him the Longstreth Award in 1930, the ASME Medal, and the Percy Nicholls Award in 1942, and the American Association of Engineering Societies the John Fritz Medal in 1952.
[src:ervin-g-bailey/ervin-g-bailey] Bailey served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in the year 1948-49.
